+# OpenClaw on GCP: Operator Defaults
+
+This runbook defines the day-1 defaults for project `hoangnb-openclaw`.
+It is the execution baseline for locked decisions `D1` through `D7` in [history/openclaw-gcp-instance-strategy/CONTEXT.md](../../history/openclaw-gcp-instance-strategy/CONTEXT.md) and the approved approach in [history/openclaw-gcp-instance-strategy/approach.md](../../history/openclaw-gcp-instance-strategy/approach.md).
+
+## Scope Boundary
+
+Day-1 scope in this feature is VM provisioning and operator runbooks only.
+Do not generate or commit OpenClaw `.env` files, Compose scaffolding, or provider secrets in this repo.
+
+## Locked Default Profile
+
+- Machine type: `e2-standard-2`
+- Disk type: `pd-balanced`
+- Disk size: `30 GiB`
+- OS family: Debian 12
+- Default region: `asia-southeast1`
+- Price-first override region: `us-central1`
+
+This profile is chosen for an always-on, medium workload with stable headroom (`D1`, `D2`, `D3`).
+
+## Sizing Guardrails
+
+- `e2-micro` is not suitable for this workload.
+- `e2-small` is minimum-only and not recommended for steady use.
+- `e2-medium` can be used only for lighter usage or temporary cost pressure.
+- `e2-standard-2` is the default for regular daily usage.
+- Escalate to larger machine types (for example `e2-standard-4`) when CPU/RAM pressure is sustained.
+
+## Disk and Retention Guardrails
+
+- Keep `30 GiB` as the default boot disk for first deployment.
+- Escalate to `50 GiB` when long-lived workspace retention, model/tool cache growth, or restore history requires more headroom.
+- Keep persistent disks and snapshot/backup steps in the operating flow (`D7`).
+
+## Region Rule
+
+Use `asia-southeast1` by default for latency-first operation.
+Allow runtime region and zone overrides in scripts (`D6`).
+Use `us-central1` when price optimization is more important than proximity.
+
+## Provisioning Model
+
+Use a two-layer model from the approved approach:
+
+1. Deterministic baseline provisioning using `gcloud` scripts and instance templates.
+2. Persistent full-environment clones from machine images when cloning an existing long-lived environment.
+
+Do not treat machine images as a replacement for deterministic baseline rebuilds.
+
+## Scripted Baseline Provisioning
+
+Baseline scripts live in `scripts/openclaw-gcp/`:
+
+- `create-template.sh`: resolves and records a specific Debian 12 image, then creates an instance template with explicit OpenClaw image/tag and explicit startup-script source.
+- Regional template operations are region-scoped, and `create-instance.sh` uses the same region when creating VMs from that template.
+- `create-instance.sh`: creates a VM from that template and can ensure the template exists first.
+
+Example flow:
+
+```bash
+bash scripts/openclaw-gcp/create-template.sh \
+  --project-id hoangnb-openclaw \
+  --openclaw-tag vX.Y.Z
+
+bash scripts/openclaw-gcp/create-instance.sh \
+  --project-id hoangnb-openclaw \
+  --instance-name oc-main \
+  --openclaw-tag vX.Y.Z
+```
+
+Rerun behavior:
+
+- `create-instance.sh` now ensures the template exists and reuses it if already present.
+- Pass `--replace-template` when you intentionally want to rebuild the template with new inputs.
+
+Security boundary:
+
+- Do not pass API keys or provider secrets via metadata or command flags.
+- Inject runtime credentials after boot via operator auth, VM service account, or Secret Manager.
+- If you use `--startup-script-url`, you must also pass `--startup-script-sha256` so the fetched content stays pinned across reruns.
+- Do not use signed or credential-bearing startup-script URLs. Keep private access outside template metadata and logs.
+
+## Persistent Clone Workflow (Machine Images)
+
+Use machine images only when you need a persistent full-environment clone of an existing, long-lived VM.
+Do not use machine images as the only provisioning path. Keep deterministic baseline rebuild scripts as the primary fresh-build mechanism.
+
+### When to use each path
+
+- Baseline rebuild (`create-template.sh` + `create-instance.sh`): clean, deterministic environment from pinned inputs.
+- Persistent clone (`create-machine-image.sh` + `spawn-from-image.sh`): copy of a known-good environment for long-lived branch environments or rollback points.
+
+### Pre-capture scrub checklist (required)
+
+Before capturing a machine image from a source VM:
+
+1. Remove local provider tokens, session artifacts, and temporary credentials.
+2. Remove or rotate any user-managed service account keys stored on disk.
+3. Remove local `.env` or secret files that should not be inherited.
+4. Confirm the source VM can still start and run OpenClaw after the scrub.
+5. Prefer VM service account + Secret Manager based credential retrieval for the cloned environment.
+
+Capture command:
+
+```bash
+bash scripts/openclaw-gcp/create-machine-image.sh \
+  --project-id hoangnb-openclaw \
+  --source-instance oc-main \
+  --source-zone asia-southeast1-a \
+  --image-name oc-image-20260324-001
+```
+
+### Spawn a persistent clone
+
+You can override target zone (and optionally machine type) at spawn time:
+
+```bash
+bash scripts/openclaw-gcp/spawn-from-image.sh \
+  --project-id hoangnb-openclaw \
+  --instance-name oc-clone-a \
+  --machine-image oc-image-20260324-001 \
+  --zone us-central1-a
+```
+
+### Post-clone credential and auth steps (required)
+
+1. Re-auth providers and runtime integrations on the new clone.
+2. Reinject credentials intentionally (manual or Secret Manager flow).
+3. Do not assume secrets copied from the source machine image are valid or allowed for continued use.
+4. Validate clone health before production use (services up, workspace accessible, no stale identity material).

